rshna is like going back from the linear progres=\r\nsion of spirituality that the Avatars manifest one after the other upto Krs=\r\nhna&quot;.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;I want to emphatically disagree with this notion that Da=\r\nsavatars of a &quot;linear progression of spirituality..upto\n Krshna&quot;.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;=\r\n&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n=\r\nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Each avatara represents an aspect of Suprem=\r\ne in a perfected form.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Maharshi Parasara equated dasavataras w=\r\nith planets. For example, Rama, Krishna and Narasimha are Sun, Moon and Mar=\r\ns, respectively.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;We also\n know that Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, =\r\nJupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu and Ketu are personifications of soul, mind, e=\r\nnergy/initiative/drive, learning spirit, wisdom/discrimination, spirit of e=\r\nnjoyment/being happy, patience/discipline, spirit of innovation/breaking ba=\r\nrriers and detachment (respectively).&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Correspondingly, each av=\r\natara is an expression of that aspect of Supreme in a perfected form. Each =\r\nstory is an example of how that aspect operates.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Lord Rama&#39;s s=\r\ntory is a perfected example of how soul operates. Lord Krishna&#39;s story is a=\r\n perfected example of how mind operates. Lord Vamana&#39;s story is a perfected=\r\n example of how wisdom/discrimination operates. Lord Narasimha&#39;s story is a=\r\n perfected example of how energy/drive/initiative operates.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&=\r\nnbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n=\r\nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Now, let us remember one basic thing. Soul in us,=\r\n mind in us, energy in us,\n learning spirit in us, wisdom in us, happiness =\r\nin us, discipline/patience in us - all these are different manifestations o=\r\nf the same Self. However, when Self manifests as these different aspects, i=\r\nt has different qualities and plays different roles. There is no comparison=\r\n between them.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;We MAY focus on one aspect of us first, perfect=\r\n it and then perfect other aspects through it. But, we need balance between=\r\n all aspects in the end. Similarly, these different aspects of Supreme Bein=\r\ng are incomparable and are in a balance working together in the Cosmos.&lt;br&gt;=\r\n&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n=\r\nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;One who is fascinated by the qualitie=\r\ns of soul may like the story that demonstrates how soul operates; one who i=\r\ns fascinated by the qualities of mind may like the story that demonstrates =\r\nhow mind operates, and one who is fascinated by the qualities of wisdom may=\r\n like the story that\n demonstrates how wisdom operates. And so on. But this=\r\n is just a matter of taste and subjective preference.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&=\r\nnbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n=\r\nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. S=\r\noul is seen as a representative of god in us, because of some basic attribu=\r\ntes of it. It is the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes.&lt;=\r\nbr&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Once mind fancies a separate existence with some agendas/desir=\r\nes, soul supports the individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy=\r\n and sees it as its dharma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect o=\r\nf this individualized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning=\r\n ability, enjoyment, discipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no=\r\n desires/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and=\r\n records all of one&#39;s agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper=\r\n fruits later\n on. It does all that despite full awareness that it is neith=\r\ner doing those karmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects o=\r\nf the individualized consciousness entertain the notion that they are doing=\r\n things and begetting the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It=\r\n sees that as its dharma and does it impassionately.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Now, does=\r\n this sound exciting? Perhaps not to all. This functionality of an impassio=\r\nnate witness supporting the play, may not seem interesting enough to some.&lt;=\r\nbr&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;On the other hand, mind has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is=\r\n constantly pursuing those agendas, getting things and achieving things. Mo=\r\nvement of mind is what keeps the individualization going!!! Though soul is =\r\nthe support for everything else in the individualized consciousness, soul i=\r\ns a witness doing its dharma impassionately. It is mind that keeps the indi=\r\nvidualization going and brings in agendas and passion and even decides/affe=\r\ncts\n every entity&#39;s dharma. That way, mind is really the &quot;boss&quot; of the indi=\r\nvidualization. No wonder Krishna&#39;s life appeals more to one who may be exci=\r\nted by this description!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=\r\n&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Lord Kris=\r\nhna is obviously awe-inspiring, but let me put Rama&#39;s life in perspective.&lt;=\r\nbr&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Rama&#39;s life demonstrates how soul operates. At a young age, he=\r\n received Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and became realized. Yet, he did what=\r\never was his &quot;dharma&quot;. He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was g=\r\niven kingdom. At the last moment, his father banished him to forest at the =\r\nbehest of his step-mother and his step-brother was given the throne. He had=\r\n no complaints. Though his father, step-mother and step-brother felt guilty=\r\n to various degrees, he himself supported and consoled all three and follow=\r\ned his dharma impassionately. Though he knew leaving Sita in the forest\n wi=\r\nth Lakshmana and going after the golden deer would cause problems, he did i=\r\nt impassionately when Sita insisted. When she was kidnapped by Ravana, he s=\r\nearched for her and fought the battle. He never faulted Sita for forcing hi=\r\nm to leave her or faulted Lakshmana for leaving her later. He accepted ever=\r\ny life situation with no complaints and did the best possible action then. =\r\nEven as he killed Ravana, he did so without hatred or anger, but as his imp=\r\nassionate dharma. Even as Ravana was dying, he went to him and respectfully=\r\n learned some subjects that were going to disappear with Ravana!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;=\r\nbr&gt;Rama is a perfect example of a liberated man with no desires or agendas =\r\nwho impassionately discharges one&#39;s dharma arising from the momentum of kar=\r\nmas before liberation. THAT is basically what soul does!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbs=\r\np;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp=\r\n;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;As another example, let us look at Lord\n Vaamana. Hi=\r\ns story is a perfect demonstration of how wisdom/discrimination operates.&lt;b=\r\nr&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;He was born as a learned pygmy. He filled the entire cosmos to =\r\nrid earth of a charitable demon king with many great qualities.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;b=\r\nr&gt;Wisdom/discrimination makes one humble and unassuming. When one is doing =\r\ngood work but tainted with demonic qualities (e.g. pride or attachment), on=\r\ne&#39;s discrimination is not pleased until that pride is suppressed. When wisd=\r\nom fills one&#39;s entire consciousness, then demonic qualities are completely =\r\nsuppressed.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp=\r\n;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Please think about the=\r\n other avataras. The stories can be understood as perfect demonstrations of=\r\n how various aspects of our consciousness operate, based on clues from Maha=\r\nrshi Parasara.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Let us not compare Dasavataras, but celebrate e=\r\nach of them separately. Of course, if you are more\n attracted to one of the=\r\nm, please think about that avatara more and develop devotion. They are ALL =\r\ncapable of relieving us from samsara.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp=\r\n;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;=\r\n&lt;br&gt;By the way, happy Hanumajjayanti to those who celebrate it today (there=\r\n are different schools of thought).&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Best regards,&lt;br&gt;Narasimha=\r\n&lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;Astrology &amp; Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAst=\r\nrologer.org &lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/blockq=\r\nuote&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;\r\n---1593584224-319266861-1367187860=:64384--\r\n\n"}}